  "notes": [
    "PREPARATION FOR THE MINOR MATH 19A: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics MATH 19B: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics MATH 23A: Vector Calculus One of the following sequence options: PHYS 5A: Introduction to Physics I AND PHYS 5L: Introduction to Physics I Laboratory PHYS 5B: Introduction to Physics II AND PHYS 5M: Introduction to Physics II Laboratory PHYS 5C: Introduction to Physics III AND PHYS 5N: Introduction to Physics III Laboratory PHYS 5D: Introduction to Physics IV OR PHYS 6A: Introductory Physics I AND PHYS 6L: Introductory Physics I Laboratory PHYS 6B: Introductory Physics II AND PHYS 6B: Introductory Physics II Laboratory PHYS 6C: Introductory Physics III AND PHYS 6N: Introductory Physics III Laboratory PHYS 5D: Introduction to Physics IV Please visit the Astronomy and Astrophysics website to learn more about this minor.",
    "UC Santa Cruz students may choose to complete one or more minors, provided they can finish all required coursework within their maximum enrollment terms and allowable credits. While a minor will appear on a student's official transcript, it will not be listed on their diploma. Pursuing a minor is a personal decision that should align with a student's educational and career goals. Students do not apply for minors when submitting their application to UC Santa Cruz. After enrolling, transfer students interested in pursuing a minor should contact the department offering the minor for guidance."
